			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Slightly modified from a post i made on the subject on my guilds board....
<br />

<br />
One of the issues brought to the table is that dps classes are too impatient to work with warrior tanks, not wanting to wait to start their burns, but I don't necessarily blame them (us.) With all the mana regen methods introduced into the game casters have a ton of mana, and it dosen't do much good sittin around. With a paladin or shadow knight those nukers can kill not just a single mob faster but kill more mobs in the same time.
<br />

<br />
I recall people talking of days of yore when nukers would do one nuke a fight and sit down to med because that is what it took to maintain a balanced mana pool. The off set ot this was that the nuker could wait till aggro was firmly established since it didn't matter when the one nuke came during the fight.
<br />

<br />
Now With VoQ, horses, SD, self regen spells, paragon, mod rods, bard songs, pot9, ft aa's, ft items Casters got mana to burn! No offense to chanters here but I would guess it can all be traced back to KEI and its long duration. Before having strong mana regen required having a specific class in the group because breeze, clarity and clarity 2 didn't have very long durations, mana regen was of limited availability. 
<br />

<br />
Then ya add in mana preservation effects and damage focus. Now mana regen got a 15% improvement, mixed with dd focus items causing even more aggro for less mana, means casters can cause more aggro, more often. At the same time non casters didn't get anything to help them very much. Melee's got vengeance items which are still farily rare and limited improvement (think tests show 10 atk = 1% increased damage) and hate procs which are unreliable (compared to mana pres focus.)
<br />

<br />
Shadow Knights, Paladins, and beastlords  however being casters, we can take advantage of the focus items. Since we use spells for aggro, 15% mana preservation equivicably means 15% more aggro spells. On top of that we get to keep up with casters mana pool regens because we can use the same things. To take it even further as hybrid tanks progress in levels we get spells that generate more aggro, a 65% slow generates a lot more aggro than a 50% slow. Larger stun, larger aggro (might even be higher level spell = more aggro.) 
<br />

<br />
Compared to a warrior who tries to grab aggro on inc with a bow might be doing on average 10 more points of damage with the first shot. The amount of hate generated by 10 points of damage is pretty small. The warrior who relied upon the aggro formula of "first to do damage + in melee range + xx damage" at level 50 is still relying on "first to do damage + in melee range + (xx + 10)." Compared to that wizard who goes from nuking for 2k to 4k the warrior dosen't gain nearly the increase in hate generation.
<br />

<br />
So all that spiel really does is delve into the problem, the question though isn't what is the problem so much as what to do to FIX the problem? And to a lesser extent do so without creating more problems?
<br />

<br />
My own thoughts are
<br />

<br />
1) Warriors shouldn't be made into a dps class/become "the master of all weapon types." There are many classes that already compete for dps positions, adding another makes more problems. As for nerfing paladins and shadow knights so that they excel only in one given weapon type (maybe pericing) is that so long as there are achiveable weapons that let paladins and sk's achieve similar DPS, then they are still making the same hate from weapons. Just means have to get the right weapon. On top of that nerfing one class to fix others is generally frowned upon.
<br />

<br />
2) What I think should be done is give warriors utility based special abilities that generate aggro. In a sense its another way to apply the idea that warriors should be the masters of combat, but I tend to think of it along the lines of called shots similar to D&amp;D. Targeted shots like: Hamstring (snare), numb leg (root), arm chop (cripple), arm numb (disable dual weild rolls for mob)etc... However once one of the abilities landed on a mob no more would be useable. It's now aware of the warriors combat prowess and is on its guard, BUT the initial use would generate a lot of aggro, and each additional swing would generate more even though it dosen't take effect. Basically it would become a second taunt.
<br />

<br />
The idea should be to add utility to warriors. I suppose in a sense its comparable to how a beastlord looks for a group, able to different roles. Can't get a slower? Grab a warrior and have em use their special that stops the mob from double attacking. I know such a thing would be a blow to the desireability for shamans, enchanters, bl's and even bards, but the real goal of EQ should be to allow more flexibility in creating groups while still trying to limit that class to performing 1-2 roles well. With a system like this a warrior would provide tankability with either slower (but still stacking with slow mind you  ;?) ), crowd control (root). Myself for example today was a buffer/haster/slower and crowd control for a LDoN run. Yeah I had Shobby to do some damage + my fists but had very little mana to nuke for increasing my dps.
<br />

<br />
Well those are my thoughts.
<br />

<br />
-Seboa<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=365340" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://www.geocities.com/hobbess007/Sig10-11-03.txt" border="0" /></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
